                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 Nelson, Bert N./109: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-04T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 4, 1931—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 4—10:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>43. The following telegram has been sent to the Legation: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“May 4, 3 p.m. My April 28, 1 p.m.<note n="51" xml:id="d880fn51">Not
                                printed.</note> The go-between returned to Hankow Saturday night and
                            reported Ked brigands declined to release Nelson and are insisting on
                            delivery of 30 tins of gasoline and in addition two sewing machines.
                            Go-between returned to Sungpu yesterday morning taking with him two
                            sewing machines and 30 tins of gasoline. He was accompanied to Sungpu by
                            Nelson’s brother, Daniel Nelson. Active military operations were started
                            against the Ked brigands in northeastern Hupeh several days ago by
                            Government troops and several towns including Chiliping, a communist
                            stronghold, have been captured <pb facs="1071" n="961" xml:id="pg_961"/>
                            by the troops under General Li Ming-chung. It is hoped that Nelson may
                            be released before these operations reach the vicinity where he is now
                            being held.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Department.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
